      strong Gastronomy 
      |in Danube Delta is based on fish. Among the usual fish dishes, one can savor the fish soup (first eating the fish, than the soup itself), fish pudding, stuffed pike, grilled fish, salt brined fish, fish schnitzels, fish meatballs, carp meatball soup, marinated fish, stockfish, scordolea (boiled and salted fish with mashed potatoes and garlic sauce).  
    p.en During holidays, one could also cook poultry. As a side dish, potatoes may be served. Dinner is served with the traditional rolled bread. This special bread signifies good omen. Another special type of bread prepared in the Danube Delta is the pampuşca also known as piroşte (Ukrainian names). This bread is coated with a syrup made of honey or sugar with poppy seeds. Along with this bread, one can also serve boiled colţunaşi (dumplings). 
    p.en The Turkish and Tartar locals do not serve any pork or alcohol. Mutton is one of the main dishes for these people. The Turkish communities serve baclavale, sarailii, kenaf and drink şerbet as a dessert.
    p.en Regarding local customs in this region, should be mentioned that in the area live communities of Romanians, Lipovans (“lipa” translates to linden tree – their icons are painted on linden wood, and in the past, these people wore sandals made of this material; these people are of Russian origins), Kahols (Ukrainian origin), Turks, Tartars, Macedo-Romanians, Bulgarians, Greeks, Armenians, Austro-Hungarians, Jews, Albanians, Germans, English, Montenegrins, Polish, Danish, Gagauz, Persians (Kiss, 1997). Among the local traditions one could mention those of Christmas and New Year, including the Goat and Bear rituals (Romanian variants) or the “melanca” (Ukrainian version), the “sorcova” well-wishing, the “sowing” ritual – throwing wheat and rice seeds to bestow wealth upon the others for the year to come (Romanian, Macedo-Romanian and Ukrainian variants). On the Epiphany Day, the young men take a bath in the frozen waters of the Danube to purify their bodies. When the fishing season starts, fishing tools are always consecrated in local rituals. Must be mentioned that local Slavonic populations pertain to the Old Rite Christian-Orthodox confession.
    p.en On the Shrove Tuesday „Lăsata Secului”, the last day before the beginning of Lent, relatives gather and serve various food rich in calories, celebrating the “preparation of nougat” with dances and joy. One of the most important religious fest in Danube Delta is the Easter of the Deads (on the first Monday after the Easter). It is then when deads are remembered and community members gather in the graveyard to pour some wine drops over the graves and serve red-painted eggs with “coliva”.
    p.en Egg represents a symbol of life, renewal, birth and resurrection. During  Easter Holidays, painted eggs are placed on a tray along with several coins and water is sprinkled over them. The ones who wash their face with this water will be rich and healthy all year long. 

    p.en One shouldn’t forget the rare sight offered by fishing activities in the DDBR. There are many traditional fishing techniques among which some are very interesting, offering moments of total satisfaction, besides the sport fishing practiced by tourists coming in the DDBR.
    p.en In the Danube Delta fishing is an everyday activity throughout the whole year (except a 60 days prohibition) using passive and active fishing tools. The effort of fishermen in the Delta are quite impressive, as they often face difficulties of all sorts, from weather conditions to gear and even state legislation - changing from one year to another. Even so, they succeed in catching fish with amazing skills. While some tradititional tools and techniques were prohibited, others are still in use. One of the most exciting ones is ice fishing. In winter, several holes are cut through the ice, and fishing nets with floating devices at hole levels is positioned under the ice. In spring, on Danube waterways are used gillnets for Danube Shad fishing.


    p.en The geographic units landscape values, including the helio-marine beaches at Sulina, St. Gheorghe, Gura Portiţei, Periboina and Grindu Chituc, can be exploited for tourism also, even in the condition of the biosphere reserve establishment. Natural and cultural values of the Danube Delta Reserve, the main attractions for visitors, are used through various FORMS of TOURISM: leisure and recreation tourism, knowledge tourism, specialized/scientific tourism, photo - safari tourism, environmental education tourism (youth special programs), water sports tourism, fishing and hunting sports tourism, rural tourism. Apart from the main access routes (river branches and some main channels) needed for the contact with human settlements and economic exploitation of natural resources, agricultural and forestry polders, fish ponds, there have been identified also a series of trails that can be used for tourism activities by providing public access to recreational areas.
